text_full: Having already gone through this process, I understand the indication that waiting to full retirement age is better; however, I qualified under my deceased husband's benefits at the age of 63. For those individuals who are able to wait until full retirement age, the advantage is much greater. If an individual is able to combine a regular retirement and full SS benefits, it will be a financial blessing to them. I elected to retire from the Federal Gov. at age 63, knowing that I would also qualify for 100% of my late husband's SS and the combined income has served me well. Some people say that starting to draw on their benefits earlier just adds on to their regular retirement benfits and they will just draw for more years. I can see where there would be a benefit to drawing SS early, if your other income/assets are very small and it is needed to live on.

text_full: I will receive more money from social security if I wait. I may not live to see any benefits if I don't get it when I can. I may not be in good enough health to enjoy it if I wait. If I get the money earlier and invest it wisely I might end up with more than if I waited. I would have to pay for medicare out of my own pocket instead of having it deducted from the social security I receive. At the time I actually made this decision, I calculated what was the break even age and it was in the 70s far to late for me to be sure I would be able to enjoy it. I have sufficient retirement income outside social security that I might as well get what I can early and enjoy it now. The amount of social security I get is so low that it doesn't make any sence to wait.
thought: I will receive more money from social security if I wait.

text_full: The longer I work, the more I am contributing to FICA, so the more the system works. For many people this is great. If I owned my own business I would probably be so involved that retirement would not be something I thought about. I already have the freedom to take a long vacation should I chose to do so. I make enough money to hire others to make repairs and modificat Right now to look at the chart and see only a minimal difference between full retirement at 66 of $1k and $1132 for age 70, you may have the foresight to realize that $132 extra per month will be needed just to make do. Right now, with no ss increase in 2 If I do not receive a pension from my state or a private company, I will need as much ss as I can possibly get, so I opt to work until I'm at least 70. I noticed that I was getting slower at my job, so opted to take early retirement at 62.  If my health is great, I can possibly get a less stressful job after retiring to supplement the small ss payment. On paper it looks good, and you budget around the small amount because you hate your job and want to get out of there, but in reality you'll be pitching pennies to survive. Having to worry about money is no fun in retirement. in order to retire early, however, I had to cash in my IRAs and 401K.  I could never read all the books or watch all the movies I wanted to when I worked, so retiring early while I still have my eyesight means I can enjoy those activities. The very worst thing I've ever heard about early retirement is that a couple, each receiving a small ss check got sick, had medical bills they could not pay (because Medicare does not cover too much), and one dies. The surviving spouse has to move into pu
thought: The longer I work, the more I am contributing to FICA, so the more the system works. For many people this is great.
thought_clean: longer work contribut system work mani peopl great

text_full: Could retire sooner Even though the benefit would be less, it would be liveable if you have other sources besides SS. If SS becomes bankrupt, at least you would collect something before it happened. Maybe consider drawing SS but investing it while not using it to live on until at an older age.  Thus safeguarding some of what we have put in before it goes bankrupt. The math pencils out to wait until full retirement age if you live to age 85 or later. Work longer, so you have more time to invest in other retirement accounts while allowing your SS payment to increase as well. Don't retire at least until you have Medicare because the cost of insurance is a real deterrant to retiring before the age of 65. Work longer so you don't have to use your nest-egg for as many years.
thought: Could retire sooner

text_full: I also will be receiving PERS benefits How will that effect my Social Security Benefit? I know it causes it to decrease, but by how much? I also know that I can claim benefits based on my ex-husbands benefits I know he is planning to retire soon at age 64 so I think my benefit would be a percentage of his 93% benefit Because we were married almost 25 years, I'm also entitled to (I think) half of his pension with Motion Picture Health and Welfare, but I've heard it went under with Enron and that there is nothing to get half of. I've only worked with LVMPD for 13 years so won't receive full benefit for PERS.  I checked with them a couple years ago, and if I had retired as of 1/02/2010 my benefit from them would have been 1551.45 a month.  I wonder how much it has increased since  I know that the percentage that I earn from PERS increase at 15 years of employment.  I'll have 15 years as of 9/22/2012.    I will be 63 years old then. I really need to talk to someone at Social Security office to find out for sure what my benefits would be based on fact that I have PERS benefits also. I wonder if they will address that later in this survey. I think I'll pull out my PERS paperwork and figure out how much my benefits would be from them at that various ages.   I also need to find out if I'll have anything coming from Motion Picture Health and Welfare.  Bud said he was going to check on that since he's looking into retiring soon.  Wonder if he's done that yet. I should just continue with survey and see what information they provide in the process before I go any further with this. Lets see, I'm actually elligible to retire now if I could afford to do so. What would be the benefit of retiring now? I'd have time to do all the projects I don't have time to do now I'd have more time to spend with family. I could spend lots of time in genealogy research I'd have time for travel.  Could see the places I haven't had time to see, or haven't taken the time to see There is no way I could afford to retire now.  I'm having trouble stretching the money to cover bills as it is.  No way I could do it on a percentage of what I make now. I need to gather more information before I can make a decision.   I need to figure out what my benefits would be from all source if I retired at various ages. I wonder where the over-all economy will be going over the next few years?  I really don't see it getting much better any time soon.  That means that I need to allow even more of a \cushion\".  My cost of living will being increasing I'm sure" I just bought a house and received new home owner discount.  That means I have to stay in the house and cannot move for at least another year and half.  I have to wait at least that long before I can retire.  Hoping property values will go up by then and  it will provide some retirement income. The longer I wait, the higher my monthly income will be at retirement.
thought: I also will be receiving PERS benefits

text_full: If you take early retirement you will end up with more money in the long run that waiting until later. You can still work part-time, if you choose, to add more money to monthly living. A negative to taking early retirement: If you work until full age, the limits are taken off your continued work. You can draw full ss and get fulltime pay without penalties. You cannot receive medicare until full retirement age. So, if you cannot afford insurance, better stay working for that benefit.

I may decide that I don't want to work anymore and would need the income.

text_full: Receiving benefits early would mean getting less money but would mean that I could get that money earlier to supplement my monthly income. If I had health issues and needed extra income, I would take my benefits earlier not only to help pay for medical expenses but also because I might think at that time that my life expectancy would not be as long as I had anticipated so there would be no n The issues of the economy may dictate that my monthly earnings from saving  and other income are not enough to cover my living costs.  Then I would have to take my benefits earlier than expected, especially since waiting for the time that I could receive  If my spouse were to die before I reach the age of 70 and my income were significantly reduced I would definitely  need to consider taking my benefits early. If taxes were to continue to go up and interest on savings would continue to be low or go even lower than they presently are I would probably need more monthly income than I had planned therefore requiring me to take benefits earlier than expected. My husband and I have already planned on taking these benefits at 70 because we will both be getting pensions before then.  We will also have other income to supplement our pensions so we can wait. We expect our monthly expenses to go down after the age of 62 as compared to what we are spending now on house payments, clothes, gas, etc. once we're not working. We will be in a lower income tax bracket and will have a bit more money just because of that fact alone.  Also our house will be paid off giving us more income each month. Our health has been good and we exercise and take care of our bodies. We expect to have long life expectancies and feel it is better to wait until 70 to take these benefits.
